%N A272534 Decimal expansion of the edge length of a regular 15-gon with unit circumradius.
%C A272534 15-gon is the first m-gon with odd composite m which is constructible (see A003401) in virtue of the fact that 15 is the product of two distinct Fermat primes (A019434). The next such case is 51-gon (m=3*17), followed by 85-gon (m=5*17), 771-gon (m=3*257), etc.
%C A272534 From _Wolfdieter Lang_, Apr 29 2018: (Start)
%C A272534 This constant appears in a historic problem posed by Adriaan van Roomen (Adrianus Romanus) in his Ideae mathematicae from 1593, solved by Vi√®te. See the Havil reference, problem 4, pp. 69-74. See also the comments in A302711 with a link to Romanus' book, Exemplum quaesitum.
%C A272534 This problem is equivalent to R(45, 2*sin(Pi/675)) = 2*sin(Pi/15), with a special case of monic Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind, named R, given in A127672. For the constant 2*sin(Pi/675) see A302716. (End)
%D A272534 Julian Havil, The Irrationals, A Story of the Numbers You Can't Count On, Princeton University Press, Princeton and Oxford, 2012, pp. 69-74.
